   "source": [
    "#Task 2: Reason about mutability and references\n",
    "# List\n",
    "values = [10, 20, 30]\n",
    "alias = values\n",
    "alias.append(40)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Values: {values}\") # [10, 20, 30]\n",
    "print(f\"Alias: {alias}\")   # [10, 20, 30, 40]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Copy\n",
    "values_copy = values.copy()\n",
    "values_copy.append(99)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Original: {values}\") # [10, 20, 30, 40]\n",
    "print(f\"Copy: {values_copy}\") # [10, 20, 30, 40, 99]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Dictionary\n",
    "record = {\"name\": \"something\"}\n",
    "record_alias = record\n",
    "record_alias[\"version\"] = 2\n",
    "\n",
    "record_copy = record.copy()\n",
    "record_copy[\"status\"] = \"active\"\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Record: {record}\")      \n",
    "print(f\"Record Copy: {record_copy}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2e1df348-bba0-4194-92c0-07d7a31558ea",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### task 2\n",
    "Lists and dictionaries in Python are mutable, meaning they can be changed after creation.\n",
    "Assigning a list to another variable (alias) does not make a copy—both point to the same object, so changes affect both.\n",
    "Using .copy() creates a new independent object, so changes to the copy do not affect the original.\n",
    "This also matters when passing objects to functions: modifying a mutable object inside a function changes the original unless you pass a copy."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "708bc85f-ee53-4f3b-8cb8-766b9b3adc16",
